18/03/19
MOTOR SUBSYSTEM: Previous motor cannot output enough power, new motor en route.
RADIO SUBSYSTEM: Completeted.
POWER SUBSYSTEM: New higher power transformer en route along with a current in rush limiter.
ARDUINO SUBSYSTEM: 12V Regulator required to dissipate 24V power from supply.
3D PRINTING: 3D printing on hold until new motor arrives.
PCB: Pending completion.

GOALS:
  Connect the new power supply to the motor and model the motor.
  Connect the new power supply to the 12v regulator and the arduino to test the temperature.
  Connect the in rush current limiter and check current through the circuit as well as temperature.
  
CHALLENGES:
  The output shaft is already 10mm so a constant radius of the coupler/pulley will be required to maintain a comfortable torque
  buffer.
  The system may require heat sinking, particularly the 12v regulator.
  
NOTES:
  A current sensing resistor may be required to help prevent stalling and thus temperature increasing in the motor.
  
THOUGHTS:
  A slower monkey is not a bad thing. It will reach up slowly for the bananas and then coast (pseudo freefall) and the motor can
  slow it down right before the bottom of its arc.
  Being a slower motor means that a lower duty cycle where the monkey is moving imperciptibly but by the end of half an hour it will
  have moved considerably, adding a sense of magic to how the monkey moves.
  Having two of these systems for both monkeys in the middle of the gym will add considerable value to the experience as well as
  help contain parties by the kids remembering not to cross to the wrong side because the floating monkeys are there.
  A spider rapelling from its web in the disco area would be very novel as well. There is potential to generate a number of
  models that complement each other whilst seamlessly working in tandem off one remote.
  
**************************************************************************************************************************************
  
22/04/19
MOTOR SUBSYSTEM: New motor arrived and works well.
RADIO SUBSYSTEM: New toggle type receiver en route.
POWER SUBSYSTEM: A reverse voltage protector is en route.
ARDUINO SUBSYSTEM: Regulator arrived and a battery can be useful to keep the Arduino on.
3D PRINTING: Will complete when PCB and props in place.
PCB: Pending completion.

GOALS:
  Set up the admin mode to calibrate the bottom point of the arc.
  Set up the code to make the monkey have a nice ramp speed at both peaks of the arc.
  Set up the code to ramp the speed through 0 - 255 so that the user can select which speed they desire.
  
CHALLENGES:
  Need aluminium output shaft and potentially heatsinks for the motor driver and the reverse voltage protector.
  Need to accomodate for heatsinks in the 3D printed case.
  Need to test the whole setup in the field.
  
NOTES:
  The toggle type will be useful as the interrupts can detect changes thus the user can turn the motor on/off, cycle speed and select
  the preferred speed, change direction and have a free button for another setting.
  
THOUGHTS:
  The 9V battery will work for a short time but cannot output much current so a higher mAh battery will likely be required for keeping
  the Arduino on.
  As there is a free button maybe it can be used to initiate the admin mode for calibrating the arc, but also, when activated, altering
  the effects of the other buttons to complete other tasks. The admin mode should be able to be turned off with the same pattern as
  was used to turn it on or go to autonomous mode after 2 min of no input.
  
  This point is important for the business model of these projects: There is potential to generate a number of
  models that complement each other whilst seamlessly working in tandem off one remote.

